**Important:** The current `handlePointerMove` in `SketchViewport.jsx` (line 337-344) has a guard that skips pointer-move events when not in a tool interaction (`if (e.buttons === 0 && !toolState.dragging && !toolState.drawing && !toolState.extruding) return;`). This guard must be relaxed to allow hover detection. Change it to always call the handler on move but let handlers decide what to do. Alternatively, add a separate `onHover` method to the handler interface.

I recommend the separate `onHover` method approach, to keep the handler pattern clean:

```javascript
// In SketchViewport.jsx handlePointerMove:
const handlePointerMove = useCallback((e) => {
  const intersection = raycast(e);
  if (!intersection) return;

  // Always call hover for snap indicators
  if (tool.onHover) {
    tool.onHover(intersection, e, toolState, viewportRef.current);
  }

  // Only call onPointerMove during active interaction
  if (e.buttons !== 0 || toolState.dragging || toolState.drawing || toolState.extruding) {
    tool.onPointerMove(intersection, e, toolState, viewportRef.current);
  }
}, [raycast, tool, toolState]);
```

Each handler implements `onHover` to update snap indicators and face highlights. For performance, raycasting on every mouse move is already happening for any active interaction; for hover-only, we are adding raycasting on idle mouse moves. This is fine since Three.js raycasting against ~50 boxes is extremely fast.

#### 8.4 `pushPullHandler3d.js` Changes

The push/pull handler snaps the extrusion distance (a scalar), not a 3D point. The inference engine can still help here: snap the extruded end position to inference points from other parts. For example, extruding a shelf outward should snap to the depth of an adjacent shelf.

```javascript
// In onPointerMove, after computing raw distance:
if (snapEnabled) {
  // Compute the end-face center position at current distance
  const endPoint = computeExtrusionEndCenter(toolState.sourcePart, toolState.faceId, distance);
  const inferencePoints = inferenceCache.getPoints(project.parts, toolState.sourcePart.id);

  // Only snap along the extrusion axis
  const axis = faceIdToAxis(toolState.faceId); // '+z' -> 'z', etc.
  const axisResult = findNearestOnAxis(endPoint, inferencePoints, axis, thresholdMm);

  if (axisResult) {
    distance = axisResult.adjustedDistance;
  } else {
    distance = snapToGrid(distance, SKETCH_GRID_MINOR);
  }
}
```

The `findNearestOnAxis` helper would be a new function in `inferenceEngine.js` that only compares coordinates along a single axis.

